# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: ocean-modeling
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:ocean-modeling/boussinesq-approximation-buoyancy] In fluid dynamics, the **Boussinesq approximation** (pronounced [businɛsk], named for Joseph Valentin Boussinesq) is used in the field of buoyancy-driven flow (also known as natural convection).
[src:ocean-modeling/boussinesq-approximation-buoyancy] It ignores density differences except where they appear in terms multiplied by g, the acceleration due to gravity.
[src:ocean-modeling/boussinesq-approximation-buoyancy] The essence of the Boussinesq approximation is that the difference in inertia is negligible but gravity is sufficiently strong to make the specific weight appreciably different between the two fluids.
[src:ocean-modeling/boussinesq-approximation-buoyancy] The existence of sound waves in a Boussinesq fluid is not possible as sound is the result of density fluctuations within a fluid.
[src:ocean-modeling/boussinesq-approximation-buoyancy] Boussinesq flows are common in nature (such as atmospheric fronts, oceanic circulation, katabatic winds), industry (dense gas dispersion, fume cupboard ventilation), and the built environment (natural ventilation, central heating).
[src:ocean-modeling/boussinesq-approximation-buoyancy] The approximation can be used to simplify the equations describing such flows, whilst still describing the flow behaviour to a high degree of accuracy.
[src:ocean-modeling/boussinesq-approximation-buoyancy] The Boussinesq approximation is applied to problems where the fluid varies in temperature (or composition) from one place to another, driving a flow of fluid and heat transfer (or mass transfer).
[src:ocean-modeling/boussinesq-approximation-buoyancy] The fluid satisfies conservation of mass, conservation of momentum and conservation of energy.
[src:ocean-modeling/boussinesq-approximation-buoyancy] In the Boussinesq approximation, variations in fluid properties other than density ρ are ignored, and density only appears when it is multiplied by g, the gravitational acceleration.
[src:ocean-modeling/boussinesq-approximation-buoyancy] where ν (nu) is the kinematic viscosity and **F** is the sum of any body forces such as gravity.
[src:ocean-modeling/boussinesq-approximation-buoyancy] where α is the coefficient of thermal expansion.
[src:ocean-modeling/boussinesq-approximation-buoyancy] The Boussinesq approximation states that the density variation is only important in the buoyancy term.
[src:ocean-modeling/boussinesq-approximation-buoyancy] In the equation for heat flow in a temperature gradient, the heat capacity per unit volume, $\rho C_{p}$ , is assumed constant and the dissipation term is ignored.
[src:ocean-modeling/boussinesq-approximation-buoyancy] where J is the rate per unit volume of internal heat production and k is the thermal conductivity.
[src:ocean-modeling/boussinesq-approximation-buoyancy] The three numbered equations are the basic convection equations in the Boussinesq approximation.
[src:ocean-modeling/boussinesq-approximation-buoyancy] The advantage of the approximation arises because when considering a flow of, say, warm and cold water of density *ρ*1 and *ρ*2 one needs only to consider a single density ρ: the difference Δ*ρ* = *ρ*1 − *ρ*2 is negligible.
[src:ocean-modeling/boussinesq-approximation-buoyancy] (Note that the denominator may be either density without affecting the result because the change would be of order ⁠ $g\left({\tfrac {\Delta \rho }{\rho }}\right)^{2}$ ⁠.) The most generally used dimensionless number would be the Richardson number and Rayleigh number.
[src:ocean-modeling/boussinesq-approximation-buoyancy] The mathematics of the flow is therefore simpler because the density ratio ⁠*ρ*1/*ρ*2⁠, a dimensionless number, does not affect the flow; the Boussinesq approximation states that it may be assumed to be exactly one.
[src:ocean-modeling/boussinesq-approximation-buoyancy] One feature of Boussinesq flows is that they look the same when viewed upside-down, provided that the identities of the fluids are reversed.
[src:ocean-modeling/boussinesq-approximation-buoyancy] The Boussinesq approximation is *inaccurate* when the dimensionless density difference ⁠Δ*ρ*/*ρ*⁠ is approximately 1, i.e. Δ*ρ* ≈ *ρ*.
[src:ocean-modeling/boussinesq-approximation-buoyancy] For example, consider an open window in a warm room.
[src:ocean-modeling/boussinesq-approximation-buoyancy] The warm air inside is less dense than the cold air outside, which flows into the room and down towards the floor.
[src:ocean-modeling/boussinesq-approximation-buoyancy] Now imagine the opposite: a cold room exposed to warm outside air.
[src:ocean-modeling/boussinesq-approximation-buoyancy] Here the air flowing in moves up toward the ceiling.
[src:ocean-modeling/boussinesq-approximation-buoyancy] If the flow is Boussinesq (and the room is otherwise symmetrical), then viewing the cold room upside down is exactly the same as viewing the warm room right-way-round.
[src:ocean-modeling/boussinesq-approximation-buoyancy] This is because the only way density enters the problem is via the reduced gravity g′ which undergoes only a sign change when changing from the warm room flow to the cold room flow.
[src:ocean-modeling/boussinesq-approximation-buoyancy] An example of a non-Boussinesq flow is bubbles rising in water.
[src:ocean-modeling/ekman-transport] There are three major wind patterns that lead to Ekman suction or pumping.
[src:ocean-modeling/ekman-transport] The first are wind patterns that are parallel to the coastline.
[src:ocean-modeling/ekman-transport] Due to the Coriolis effect, surface water moves at a 90° angle to the wind current.
[src:ocean-modeling/ekman-transport] If the wind moves in a direction causing the water to be pulled away from the coast then Ekman suction will occur.
[src:ocean-modeling/ekman-transport] On the other hand, if the wind is moving in such a way that surface waters move towards the shoreline then Ekman pumping will take place.
[src:ocean-modeling/ekman-transport] The second mechanism of wind currents resulting in Ekman transfer is the Trade Winds both north and south of the equator pulling surface waters towards the poles.
[src:ocean-modeling/ekman-transport] There is a great deal of upwelling Ekman suction at the equator because water is being pulled northward north of the equator and southward south of the equator.
[src:ocean-modeling/ekman-transport] This leads to a divergence in the water, resulting in Ekman suction, and therefore, upwelling.
[src:ocean-modeling/ekman-transport] The third wind pattern influencing Ekman transfer is large-scale wind patterns in the open ocean.
[src:ocean-modeling/ekman-transport] Open ocean wind circulation can lead to gyre-like structures of piled up sea surface water resulting in horizontal gradients of sea surface height.
[src:ocean-modeling/ekman-transport] This pile up of water causes the water to have a downward flow and suction, due to gravity and mass balance.
[src:ocean-modeling/ekman-transport] Ekman pumping downward in the central ocean is a consequence of this convergence of water.
[src:ocean-modeling/ekman-transport] Ekman suction is the component of Ekman transport that results in areas of upwelling due to the divergence of water.
[src:ocean-modeling/ekman-transport] Returning to the concept of mass conservation, any water displaced by Ekman transport must be replenished.
[src:ocean-modeling/ekman-transport] As the water diverges it creates space and acts as a suction in order to fill in the space by pulling up, or upwelling, deep sea water to the euphotic zone.
[src:ocean-modeling/ekman-transport] Ekman suction has major consequences for the biogeochemical processes in the area because it leads to upwelling.
[src:ocean-modeling/ekman-transport] Upwelling carries nutrient rich, and cold deep-sea water to the euphotic zone, promoting phytoplankton blooms and kickstarting an extremely productive environment.
[src:ocean-modeling/ekman-transport] Areas of upwelling lead to the promotion of fisheries with nearly half of the world's fish catch coming from areas of upwelling.
[src:ocean-modeling/ekman-transport] Ekman suction occurs both along coastlines and in the open ocean, but also occurs along the equator.
[src:ocean-modeling/ekman-transport] Along the Pacific coastline of California, Central America, and Peru, as well as along the Atlantic coastline of Africa there are areas of upwelling due to Ekman suction, as the currents move equatorwards.
[src:ocean-modeling/ekman-transport] Due to the Coriolis effect the surface water moves 90° to the left (in the Southern Hemisphere, as it travels toward the equator) of the wind current, therefore causing the water to diverge from the coast boundary, leading to Ekman suction.
[src:ocean-modeling/ekman-transport] Additionally, there are areas of upwelling as a consequence of Ekman suction where the Polar Easterlies winds meet the Westerlies in the subpolar regions north of the subtropics, as well as where the Northeast Trade Winds meet the Southeast Trade Winds along the Equator.
[src:ocean-modeling/ekman-transport] Ekman pumping is the component of Ekman transport that results in areas of downwelling due to the convergence of water.
[src:ocean-modeling/ekman-transport] As discussed above, the concept of mass conservation requires that a pile up of surface water must be pushed downward.
[src:ocean-modeling/ekman-transport] This pile up of warm, nutrient-poor surface water gets pumped vertically down the water column, resulting in areas of downwelling.
[src:ocean-modeling/ekman-transport] Ekman pumping has dramatic impacts on the surrounding environments.
[src:ocean-modeling/ekman-transport] Downwelling, due to Ekman pumping, leads to nutrient poor waters, therefore reducing the biological productivity of the area.
[src:ocean-modeling/ekman-transport] Additionally, it transports heat and dissolved oxygen vertically down the water column as warm oxygen rich surface water is being pumped towards the deep ocean water.
[src:ocean-modeling/ekman-transport] Ekman pumping can be found along the coasts as well as in the open ocean.
[src:ocean-modeling/ekman-transport] Along the Pacific Coast in the Southern Hemisphere northerly winds move parallel to the coastline.
[src:ocean-modeling/ekman-transport] Due to the Coriolis effect the surface water gets pulled 90° to the left of the wind current, therefore causing the water to converge along the coast boundary, leading to Ekman pumping.
[src:ocean-modeling/ekman-transport] In the open ocean Ekman pumping occurs with gyres.
[src:ocean-modeling/ekman-transport] Specifically, in the subtropics, between 20°N and 50°N, there is Ekman pumping as the tradewinds shift to westerlies causing a pile up of surface water.
[src:ocean-modeling/ekman-transport] Some assumptions of the fluid dynamics involved in the process must be made in order to simplify the process to a point where it is solvable.
[src:ocean-modeling/ekman-transport] where $\tau \,\!$ is the wind stress, $\rho \,\!$ is the density, $u\,\!$ is the east–west velocity, and $v\,\!$ is the north–south velocity.
[src:ocean-modeling/ekman-transport] Here $M_{x}\,\!$ and $M_{y}\,\!$ represent the zonal and meridional mass transport terms with units of mass per unit time per unit length.
[src:ocean-modeling/ekman-transport] Contrarily to common logic, north–south winds cause mass transport in the east–west direction.
[src:ocean-modeling/ekman-transport] In order to understand the vertical velocity structure of the water column, equations **1** and **2** can be rewritten in terms of the vertical eddy viscosity term.
[src:ocean-modeling/ekman-transport] where $A_{z}\,\!$ is the vertical eddy viscosity coefficient.
[src:ocean-modeling/ekman-transport] Things can be further simplified by considering wind blowing in the *y*-direction only.
[src:ocean-modeling/ekman-transport] By solving this at *z*=0, the surface current is found to be (as expected) 45 degrees to the right (left) of the wind in the Northern (Southern) Hemisphere.
[src:ocean-modeling/ekman-transport] This also gives the expected shape of the Ekman spiral, both in magnitude and direction.
[src:ocean-modeling/ekman-transport] Integrating these equations over the Ekman layer shows that the net Ekman transport term is 90 degrees to the right (left) of the wind in the Northern (Southern) Hemisphere.
[src:ocean-modeling/ekman-transport] The Ekman theory describing wind-induced current on a rotating planet explains why surface currents in the Northern Hemisphere are generally deflected to the right of wind direction, and in the Southern Hemisphere to the left in most cases.
[src:ocean-modeling/ekman-transport] There are also solutions for opposite deflections at periods shorter than the local inertial period, which were not mentioned by Ekman, and are seldom observed.
[src:ocean-modeling/ekman-transport] A major example of this effect occurs in the Bay of Bengal, where surface flow is offset to the left of wind direction in the Northern Hemisphere.
[src:ocean-modeling/ekman-transport] Ekman's theory can be refined to include this case.
[src:ocean-modeling/ekman-transport] Ekman developed the theory of the Ekman layer after Fridtjof Nansen observed that ice drifts at an angle of 20°–40° to the right of the prevailing wind direction while on an Arctic expedition aboard the Fram.
[src:ocean-modeling/ekman-transport] Nansen asked his colleague, Vilhelm Bjerknes to set one of his students upon study of the problem.
[src:ocean-modeling/ekman-transport] Bjerknes tapped Ekman, who presented his results in 1902 as his doctoral thesis.
[src:ocean-modeling/ekman-transport] Ekman theory explains the theoretical state of circulation if water currents were driven only by the transfer of momentum from the wind.
[src:ocean-modeling/ekman-transport] In the physical world, this is difficult to observe because of the influences of many simultaneous current driving forces (for example, pressure and density gradients).
[src:ocean-modeling/ekman-transport] Though the following theory technically applies to the idealized situation involving only wind forces, Ekman motion describes the wind-driven portion of circulation seen in the surface layer.
[src:ocean-modeling/ekman-transport] Surface currents flow at a 45° angle to the wind due to a balance between the Coriolis force and the drags generated by the wind and the water.
[src:ocean-modeling/ekman-transport] If the ocean is divided vertically into thin layers, the magnitude of the velocity (the speed) decreases from a maximum at the surface until it dissipates.
[src:ocean-modeling/ekman-transport] The direction also shifts slightly across each subsequent layer (right in the Northern Hemisphere and left in the Southern Hemisphere).
[src:ocean-modeling/ekman-transport] The layer of water from the surface to the point of dissipation of this spiral is known as the *Ekman layer*.
[src:ocean-modeling/ekman-transport] If all flow over the Ekman layer is integrated, the net transportation is at 90° to the right (left) of the surface wind in the Northern (Southern) Hemisphere.
[src:ocean-modeling/ekman-transport] The **Ekman spiral** is an arrangement of ocean currents: the directions of horizontal current appear to twist as the depth changes.
[src:ocean-modeling/ekman-transport] The oceanic wind driven Ekman spiral is the result of a force balance created by a shear stress force, Coriolis force and the water drag.
[src:ocean-modeling/ekman-transport] This force balance gives a resulting current of the water different from the winds.
[src:ocean-modeling/ekman-transport] In the ocean, there are two places where the Ekman spiral can be observed.
[src:ocean-modeling/ekman-transport] At the surface of the ocean, the shear stress force corresponds with the wind stress force.
[src:ocean-modeling/ekman-transport] At the bottom of the ocean, the shear stress force is created by friction with the ocean floor.
[src:ocean-modeling/ekman-transport] This phenomenon was first observed at the surface by the Norwegian oceanographer Fridtjof Nansen during his Fram expedition.
[src:ocean-modeling/ekman-transport] He noticed that icebergs did not drift in the same direction as the wind.
[src:ocean-modeling/ekman-transport] His student, the Swedish oceanographer Vagn Walfrid Ekman, was the first person to physically explain this process.
[src:ocean-modeling/ekman-transport] In order to derive the properties of an Ekman spiral a look is taken at a uniform, horizontal geostrophic interior flow in a homogeneous fluid.
[src:ocean-modeling/ekman-transport] This flow will be denoted by ${\vec {u}}=({\bar {u}},{\bar {v}})$ , where the two components are constant because of uniformity.
[src:ocean-modeling/ekman-transport] Another result of this property is that the horizontal gradients will equal zero.
[src:ocean-modeling/ekman-transport] As a result, the continuity equation will yield, ${\frac {\partial w}{\partial z}}=0$ .
[src:ocean-modeling/ekman-transport] Note that the concerning interior flow is horizontal, so $w=0$ at all depths, even in the boundary layers.
[src:ocean-modeling/ekman-transport] Where f is the Coriolis parameter, $\rho _{0}$ the fluid density and $\nu _{E}$ the eddy viscosity, which are all taken as a constant here for simplicity.
[src:ocean-modeling/ekman-transport] These parameters have a small variance on the scale of an Ekman spiral, thus this approximation will hold.
[src:ocean-modeling/ekman-transport] A uniform flow requires a uniformly varying pressure gradient.
[src:ocean-modeling/ekman-transport] Using the last of the three equations at the top of this section, yields that the pressure is independent of depth.
[src:ocean-modeling/ekman-transport] $u={\bar {u}}+Ae^{\lambda z}$ and $v={\bar {v}}+Be^{\lambda z}$ will suffice as a solution to the differential equations above.
[src:ocean-modeling/ekman-transport] After substitution of these possible solutions in the same equations, $\nu _{E}^{2}\lambda ^{4}+f^{2}=0$ will follow.
[src:ocean-modeling/ekman-transport] Because of the no-slip condition at the bottom and the constant interior flow for $z\gg d$ , coefficients A and B can be determined.
[src:ocean-modeling/ekman-transport] Note that the velocity vector will approach the values of the interior flow, when the z takes the order of d .
[src:ocean-modeling/ekman-transport] This is the reason why d is defined as the thickness of the Ekman layer.
[src:ocean-modeling/ekman-transport] The solution for the flow forming the bottom Ekman spiral was a result of the shear stress exerted on the flow by the bottom.
[src:ocean-modeling/ekman-transport] Logically, wherever shear stress can be exerted on a flow, Ekman spirals will form.
[src:ocean-modeling/ekman-transport] This is the case at the air–water interface, because of wind.
[src:ocean-modeling/ekman-transport] A situation is considered where a wind stress ${\vec {\tau }}=(\tau _{x},\tau _{y})$ is exerted along a water-surface with an interior flow ${\vec {u}}=(u,v)$ beneath.
[src:ocean-modeling/ekman-transport] Again, the flow is uniform, has a geostrophic interior and is homogeneous fluid.
[src:ocean-modeling/ekman-transport] Some differences with respect to the bottom Ekman spiral emerge.
[src:ocean-modeling/ekman-transport] The deviation from the interior flow is exclusively dependent on the wind stress and not on the interior flow.
[src:ocean-modeling/ekman-transport] Whereas in the case of the bottom Ekman spiral, the deviation is determined by the interior flow.
[src:ocean-modeling/ekman-transport] The wind-driven component of the flow is inversely proportional with respect to the Ekman-layer thickness d .
[src:ocean-modeling/ekman-transport] So if the layer thickness is small, because of a small viscosity of the fluid for example, this component could be very large.
[src:ocean-modeling/ekman-transport] At last, the flow at the surface is 45 degrees to the right on the Northern Hemisphere and 45 degrees to the left on the Southern Hemisphere with respect to the wind-direction.
[src:ocean-modeling/ekman-transport] In case of the bottom Ekman spiral, this is the other way around.
[src:ocean-modeling/ekman-transport] The equations and assumptions above are not representative for the actual observations of the Ekman spiral.
[src:ocean-modeling/ekman-transport] The differences between the theory and the observations are that the angle is between 5–20 degrees instead of the 45 degrees as expected and that the Ekman layer depth and thus the Ekman spiral is less deep than expected.
[src:ocean-modeling/ekman-transport] There are three main factors which contribute to the reason why this is, stratification, turbulence and horizontal gradients.
[src:ocean-modeling/ekman-transport] Other less important factors which play a role in this are the Stokes drift, waves and the Stokes-Coriolis force.
[src:ocean-modeling/ekman-transport] The **Ekman layer** is the layer in a fluid where there is a force balance between pressure gradient force, Coriolis force and turbulent drag.
[src:ocean-modeling/ekman-transport] It was first described by Vagn Walfrid Ekman.
[src:ocean-modeling/ekman-transport] Ekman layers occur both in the atmosphere and in the ocean.
[src:ocean-modeling/ekman-transport] The first type occurs at the surface of the ocean and is forced by surface winds, which act as a drag on the surface of the ocean.
[src:ocean-modeling/ekman-transport] The second type occurs at the bottom of the atmosphere and ocean, where frictional forces are associated with flow over rough surfaces.
[src:ocean-modeling/ekman-transport] The mathematical formulation of the Ekman layer begins by assuming a neutrally stratified fluid, a balance between the forces of pressure gradient, Coriolis and turbulent drag.
[src:ocean-modeling/ekman-transport] where $\ u$ and $\ v$ are the velocities in the $\ x$ and $\ y$ directions, respectively, $\ f$ is the local Coriolis parameter, and $\ K_{m}$ is the diffusive eddy viscosity, which can be derived using mixing length theory.
[src:ocean-modeling/ekman-transport] Note that p is a modified pressure: we have incorporated the hydrostatic of the pressure, to take account of gravity.
[src:ocean-modeling/ekman-transport] There are many regions where an Ekman layer is theoretically plausible; they include the bottom of the atmosphere, near the surface of the earth and ocean, the bottom of the ocean, near the sea floor and at the top of the ocean, near the air-water interface.
[src:ocean-modeling/ekman-transport] Different boundary conditions are appropriate for each of these different situations.
[src:ocean-modeling/ekman-transport] Each of these situations can be accounted for through the boundary conditions applied to the resulting system of ordinary differential equations.
[src:ocean-modeling/ekman-transport] The separate cases of top and bottom boundary layers are shown below.
[src:ocean-modeling/ekman-transport] where $\ \tau ^{x}$ and $\ \tau ^{y}$ are the components of the surface stress, $\ \tau$ , of the wind field or ice layer at the top of the ocean, and $\ A\equiv \rho K_{m}$ is the dynamic viscosity.
[src:ocean-modeling/ekman-transport] For the boundary condition on the other side, as $\ z\to -\infty :u\to u_{g},v\to v_{g}$ , where $\ u_{g}$ and $\ v_{g}$ are the geostrophic flows in the $\ x$ and $\ y$ directions.
[src:ocean-modeling/ekman-transport] The value d is called the Ekman layer depth, and gives an indication of the penetration depth of wind-induced turbulent mixing in the ocean.
[src:ocean-modeling/ekman-transport] Note that it varies on two parameters: the turbulent diffusivity $K_{m}$ , and the latitude, as encapsulated by f .
[src:ocean-modeling/ekman-transport] This Ekman depth prediction does not always agree precisely with observations.
[src:ocean-modeling/ekman-transport] This variation of horizontal velocity with depth ( $-z$ ) is referred to as the Ekman spiral, diagrammed above and at right.
[src:ocean-modeling/ekman-transport] Note that when vertically-integrated, the volume transport associated with the Ekman spiral is to the right of the wind direction in the Northern Hemisphere.
[src:ocean-modeling/ekman-transport] and because it is difficult to design instruments with great enough sensitivity to observe the velocity profile in the ocean.
[src:ocean-modeling/ekman-transport] The bottom Ekman layer can readily be observed in a rotating cylindrical tank of water by dropping in dye and changing the rotation rate slightly.
[src:ocean-modeling/ekman-transport] Surface Ekman layers can also be observed in rotating tanks.
[src:ocean-modeling/ekman-transport] In the atmosphere, the Ekman solution generally overstates the magnitude of the horizontal wind field because it does not account for the velocity shear in the surface layer.
[src:ocean-modeling/ekman-transport] Splitting the planetary boundary layer into the surface layer and the Ekman layer generally yields more accurate results.
[src:ocean-modeling/ekman-transport] The Ekman layer, with its distinguishing feature the Ekman spiral, is rarely observed in the ocean.
[src:ocean-modeling/ekman-transport] The Ekman layer near the surface of the ocean extends only about 10 – 20 meters deep, and instrumentation sensitive enough to observe a velocity profile in such a shallow depth has only been available since around 1980.
[src:ocean-modeling/ekman-transport] Also, wind waves modify the flow near the surface, and make observations close to the surface rather difficult.
[src:ocean-modeling/ekman-transport] Observations of the Ekman layer have only been possible since the development of robust surface moorings and sensitive current meters.
[src:ocean-modeling/ekman-transport] Ekman himself developed a current meter to observe the spiral that bears his name, but was not successful.
[src:ocean-modeling/ekman-transport] The Vector Measuring Current Meter and the Acoustic Doppler Current Profiler are both used to measure current.
[src:ocean-modeling/ekman-transport] The first documented observations of an Ekman-like spiral in the ocean were made in the Arctic Ocean from a drifting ice floe in 1958.
[src:ocean-modeling/ekman-transport] Common to several of these observations spirals were found to be "compressed", displaying larger estimates of eddy viscosity when considering the rate of rotation with depth than the eddy viscosity derived from considering the rate of decay of speed.
[src:ocean-modeling/ocean-general-circulation-model] The first generation of OGCMs assumed “rigid lid” to eliminate high-speed external gravity waves.
[src:ocean-modeling/ocean-general-circulation-model] According to CFL criteria without those fast waves, we can use a bigger time step, which is not so computationally expensive.
[src:ocean-modeling/ocean-general-circulation-model] But it also filtered those ocean tides and other waves having the speed of tsunamis.
[src:ocean-modeling/ocean-general-circulation-model] Within this assumption, Kirk Bryan and co-worker Micheal Cox developed a 2D model, a 3D box model, and then a model of full circulation in GFDL, with variable density as well, for the world ocean with its complex coastline and bottom topography.
[src:ocean-modeling/ocean-general-circulation-model] The first application with specified global geometry was done in the early 1970s.
[src:ocean-modeling/ocean-general-circulation-model] Cox designed a 2° latitude-longitude grid with up to 12 vertical levels at each point.
[src:ocean-modeling/ocean-general-circulation-model] With more and more research on ocean model, mesoscale phenomenon, e.g. most ocean currents have cross-stream dimensions equal to Rossby radius of deformation, started to get more awareness.
[src:ocean-modeling/ocean-general-circulation-model] However, in order to analyze those eddies and currents in numerical models, we need grid spacing to be approximately 20 km in middle latitudes.
[src:ocean-modeling/ocean-general-circulation-model] Thanks to those faster computers and further filtering the equations in advance to remove internal gravity waves, those major currents and low-frequency eddies then can be resolved, one example is the three-layer quasi-geostrophic models designed by Holland.
[src:ocean-modeling/ocean-general-circulation-model] In the late 1980s, simulations could finally be undertaken using the GFDL formulation with eddies marginally resolved over extensive domains and with observed winds and some atmospheric influence on density.
[src:ocean-modeling/ocean-general-circulation-model] Furthermore, these simulations with high enough resolution such as the Southern Ocean south of latitude 25°, the North Atlantic, and the World Ocean without the Arctic provided first side-by-side comparison with data.
[src:ocean-modeling/ocean-general-circulation-model] Early in the 1990s, for those large-scale and eddies resolvable models, the computer requirement for the 2D ancillary problem associated with the rigid lid approximation was becoming excessive.
[src:ocean-modeling/ocean-general-circulation-model] Furthermore, in order to predict tidal effects or compare height data from satellites, methods were developed to predict the height and pressure of the ocean surface directly.
[src:ocean-modeling/ocean-general-circulation-model] For example, one method is to treat the free surface and the vertically averaged velocity using many small steps in time for each single step of the full 3D model.
[src:ocean-modeling/ocean-general-circulation-model] Another method developed at Los Alamos National Laboratory solves the same 2D equations using an implicit method for the free surface.
[src:ocean-modeling/ocean-general-circulation-model] OGCMs play a critical role in Earth system model.
[src:ocean-modeling/ocean-general-circulation-model] They maintain the thermal balance as they transport energy from tropical to the polar latitudes.
[src:ocean-modeling/ocean-general-circulation-model] Oceans are a kind of undersampled nature fluid system, so by using OGCMs we can fill in those data blank and improve understanding of basic processes and their interconnectedness, as well as to help interpret sparse observations.
[src:ocean-modeling/ocean-general-circulation-model] Even though, simpler models can be used to estimate climate response, only OGCM can be used conjunction with atmospheric general circulation model to estimate global climate change.
[src:ocean-modeling/ocean-general-circulation-model] There are different types grid types that can be used by OGCMs.
[src:ocean-modeling/ocean-general-circulation-model] There is often a separation between vertical and horizontal grids.
[src:ocean-modeling/ocean-general-circulation-model] Most models use one of the following horizontal grid types.
[src:ocean-modeling/ocean-general-circulation-model] Finite differences grids are the most common grid types for OGCMs.
[src:ocean-modeling/ocean-general-circulation-model] For the grids, the Arakawa Grids are often used.
[src:ocean-modeling/ocean-general-circulation-model] On the A grid all quantities are calculated on a single point.
[src:ocean-modeling/ocean-general-circulation-model] This was only used in some of the earliest OGCMs.
[src:ocean-modeling/ocean-general-circulation-model] However, it was quickly realized that the solutions were extremely poor.
[src:ocean-modeling/ocean-general-circulation-model] The B grid has the velocity components on the edges of the Temperature grid boxes.
[src:ocean-modeling/ocean-general-circulation-model] While the C grid separates these velocity components in an u and v component.
[src:ocean-modeling/ocean-general-circulation-model] Both are still used presently in different models.
[src:ocean-modeling/ocean-general-circulation-model] It is also possible to have a so-called Nested Grid Model.
[src:ocean-modeling/ocean-general-circulation-model] A nested grid model is an adaptation of the finite differences grid in which some parts have a higher density of grid points.
[src:ocean-modeling/ocean-general-circulation-model] Sometimes models use a finite element grid.
[src:ocean-modeling/ocean-general-circulation-model] Here, the variables are solved on a triangular grid.
[src:ocean-modeling/ocean-general-circulation-model] The big advantage of finite element grids is that it allows flexible resolution throughout the domain of the model.
[src:ocean-modeling/ocean-general-circulation-model] This is especially useful when studying a flow in a near a coastal environment as the coast can be more easily mapped.
[src:ocean-modeling/ocean-general-circulation-model] The spectral grids are the least used grids for OGCMs, while being widely used in atmospheric general circulation models.
[src:ocean-modeling/ocean-general-circulation-model] They are harder to use for ocean modelling because of the more complicated boundary conditions in the ocean compared to atmospheric models where they are extensively used.
[src:ocean-modeling/ocean-general-circulation-model] The vertical grids used for ocean general circulation models are often different from their atmospheric counterparts.
[src:ocean-modeling/ocean-general-circulation-model] Atmospheric models often use pressure as a vertical coordinate because of its isentropic nature.
[src:ocean-modeling/ocean-general-circulation-model] The z coordinate system in which height is taken as a coordinate is the simplest type of system to implement.
[src:ocean-modeling/ocean-general-circulation-model] The layers are often of varying depth with the layers near the top of the ocean being thinner than the deeper layers.
[src:ocean-modeling/ocean-general-circulation-model] This is because the features nearer to the surface happen on smaller scales.
[src:ocean-modeling/ocean-general-circulation-model] Z-coordinate systems have difficulties representing the bottom boundary layer and downslope flow due to odd diabatic mixing.
[src:ocean-modeling/ocean-general-circulation-model] In a sigma coordinate system the bottom topography determines the thickness of the vertical layer at each horizontal grid point.
[src:ocean-modeling/ocean-general-circulation-model] Similarly to the Z coordinate system the layers are often more closely spaced near the surface and/or the bottom than they are in the interior.
[src:ocean-modeling/ocean-general-circulation-model] Sigma coordinates allow the boundary layer to be better represented but have difficulties with pressure gradient errors when sharp bottom topography features are not smoothed out.
[src:ocean-modeling/ocean-general-circulation-model] Isopycnal models model the potential density at a given pressure level as the vertical coordinate.
[src:ocean-modeling/ocean-general-circulation-model] The layers thus vary in thickness throughout the domain.
[src:ocean-modeling/ocean-general-circulation-model] This type of model is particularly useful when studying tracer transport.
[src:ocean-modeling/ocean-general-circulation-model] This is because tracers often move along lines of constant density.
[src:ocean-modeling/ocean-general-circulation-model] Isopycnal models have a subtle difference with layered models.
[src:ocean-modeling/ocean-general-circulation-model] The main difference is whether the model allows the vanishing of the isopycnals.
[src:ocean-modeling/ocean-general-circulation-model] For layered models the isopycnals are not allowed to vanish which has computational speed benefits.
[src:ocean-modeling/ocean-general-circulation-model] Molecular friction rarely upsets the dominant balances (geostrophic and hydrostatic) in the ocean.
[src:ocean-modeling/ocean-general-circulation-model] With kinematic viscosities of v=10−6m 2 s−1 the Ekman number is several orders of magnitude smaller than unity; therefore, molecular frictional forces are certainly negligible for large-scale oceanic motions.
[src:ocean-modeling/ocean-general-circulation-model] A similar argument holds for the tracer equations, where the molecular thermodiffusivity and salt diffusivity lead to Reynolds number of negligible magnitude, which means the molecular diffusive time scales are much longer than advective time scale.
[src:ocean-modeling/ocean-general-circulation-model] So we can thus safely conclude that the direct effects of molecular processes are insignificant for large-scale.
[src:ocean-modeling/ocean-general-circulation-model] Yet the molecular friction is essential somewhere.
[src:ocean-modeling/ocean-general-circulation-model] The point is that large-scale motions in the ocean interacted with other scales by the nonlinearities in primitive equation.
[src:ocean-modeling/ocean-general-circulation-model] We can show that by Reynolds approach, which will leads to the closure problem.
[src:ocean-modeling/ocean-general-circulation-model] That means new variables arise at each level in the Reynolds averaging procedure.
[src:ocean-modeling/ocean-general-circulation-model] This leads to the need of parameterization scheme to account for those sub grid scale effects.
[src:ocean-modeling/ocean-general-circulation-model] Here is a schematic “family tree” of subgridscale (SGS) mixing schemes.
[src:ocean-modeling/ocean-general-circulation-model] Although there is a considerable degree of overlap and interrelatedness among the huge variety of schemes in use today, several branch points maybe defined.
[src:ocean-modeling/ocean-general-circulation-model] Most importantly, the approaches for lateral and vertical subgridscale closure vary considerably.
[src:ocean-modeling/ocean-general-circulation-model] Filters and higher-order operators are used to remove small-scale noise that is numerically necessary.
[src:ocean-modeling/ocean-general-circulation-model] Those special dynamical parameterizations (topographic stress, eddy thickness diffusion and convection) are becoming available for certain processes.
[src:ocean-modeling/ocean-general-circulation-model] In the vertical, the surface mixed layer (sml) has historically received special attention because of its important role in air-sea exchange.
[src:ocean-modeling/ocean-general-circulation-model] Now there are so many schemes can be chose from: Price-Weller-Pinkel, Pacanowksi and Philander, bulk, Mellor-Yamada and k-profile parameterization (KPP) schemes.
[src:ocean-modeling/ocean-general-circulation-model] Adaptive (non-constant) mixing length schemes are widely used for parameterization of both lateral and vertical mixing.
[src:ocean-modeling/ocean-general-circulation-model] In the horizontal, parameterizations dependent on the rates of stress and strain (Smagroinsky), grid spacing and Reynolds number (Re) have been advocated.
[src:ocean-modeling/ocean-general-circulation-model] In the vertical, vertical mixing as a function stability frequency (N^2) and/or Richardson number are historically prevalent.
[src:ocean-modeling/ocean-general-circulation-model] The rotated mixing tensors scheme is the one considering the angle of the principle direction of mixing, as for in the main thermocline, mixing along isopycnals dominates diapycnal mixing.
[src:ocean-modeling/ocean-general-circulation-model] Therefore, the principle direction of mixing is neither strictly vertical nor purely horizontal, but a spatially variable mixture of the two.
[src:ocean-modeling/ocean-general-circulation-model] OGCMs require a long spin-up time to be able to realistically represent the studied basins.
[src:ocean-modeling/ocean-general-circulation-model] Spin-up time is the time a model needs to reach a certain equilibrium.
[src:ocean-modeling/ocean-general-circulation-model] This equilibrium is often defined as a statistical parameter at which the change over time of a range of variables gets below a set threshold for a certain number of simulation timesteps.
[src:ocean-modeling/ocean-general-circulation-model] For OGCMs of a global scale it is often a challenge to reach this state.
[src:ocean-modeling/ocean-general-circulation-model] It can take thousands of model years to reach an equilibrium state for a model.
[src:ocean-modeling/ocean-general-circulation-model] The speed at which this equilibrium is reached is determined by slow processes below the thermocline.
[src:ocean-modeling/ocean-general-circulation-model] There have been many attempts to decrease the spin-up time of OGCMs.
[src:ocean-modeling/ocean-general-circulation-model] To accelerate the convergence of a model, several methods have been proposed.
[src:ocean-modeling/ocean-general-circulation-model] Better initial conditions significantly decrease the time a model needs to spin-up.
[src:ocean-modeling/ocean-general-circulation-model] However, this is not always possible, especially for the deep ocean.
[src:ocean-modeling/ocean-general-circulation-model] Another approach is the distorted physics approach.
[src:ocean-modeling/ocean-general-circulation-model] This works on the basis that the ocean has processes on relatively short time scales above the thermocline.
[src:ocean-modeling/ocean-general-circulation-model] While processes below the thermocline are often diffusive and very slow.
[src:ocean-modeling/ocean-general-circulation-model] The acceleration of these processes is achieved by decreasing the local heat capacity, while not changing the transport and the mixing of heat.
[src:ocean-modeling/ocean-general-circulation-model] This makes the speed of reaching equilibrium for these models much quicker and nearly as efficient as atmospheric models with similar resolution.
[src:ocean-modeling/ocean-general-circulation-model] This method is very successful as there is (almost) no change to the final solution of the model.
[src:ocean-modeling/ocean-general-circulation-model] It is also possible to reduce the spin-up time by exponential extrapolation.
[src:ocean-modeling/ocean-general-circulation-model] In this method, the temperature and salinity fields are repeatedly extrapolated with the assumption that they exponentially decay towards their equilibrium value.
[src:ocean-modeling/ocean-general-circulation-model] This method can in some cases reduce the spin-up time by a factor of two or three.
[src:ocean-modeling/ocean-general-circulation-model] A third proposed method is the jacobian–free Newton–Krylov method.
[src:ocean-modeling/ocean-general-circulation-model] This method uses the matrix-vector products obtained from an explicit OGCM's jacobian.
[src:ocean-modeling/ocean-general-circulation-model] The method can be applied to many existing explicit OGCMs and can significantly speed up the spin-up time.
[src:ocean-modeling/ocean-general-circulation-model] OGCMs and AGCMs have much in common, such as, the equations of motion and the numerical techniques.
[src:ocean-modeling/ocean-general-circulation-model] However, OGCMs have some unique features.
[src:ocean-modeling/ocean-general-circulation-model] For example, the atmosphere is forced thermally throughout its volume, the ocean is forced both thermally and mechanically primarily at its surface, in addition, the geometry of ocean basins is very complex.
[src:ocean-modeling/ocean-general-circulation-model] The boundary conditions are totally different.
[src:ocean-modeling/ocean-general-circulation-model] For ocean models, we need to consider those narrow but important boundary layers on nearly all bounding surfaces as well as within the oceanic interior.
[src:ocean-modeling/ocean-general-circulation-model] These boundary conditions on ocean flows are difficult to define and to parameterize, which results in a high computationally demand.
[src:ocean-modeling/ocean-general-circulation-model] Ocean modeling is also strongly constrained by the existence in much of the world's oceans of mesoscale eddies with time and space scales, respectively, of weeks to months and tens to hundreds of kilometers.
[src:ocean-modeling/ocean-general-circulation-model] Dynamically, these nearly geostrophic turbulent eddies are the oceanographic counterparts of the atmospheric synoptic scale.
[src:ocean-modeling/ocean-general-circulation-model] Nevertheless, there are important differences.
[src:ocean-modeling/ocean-general-circulation-model] First, ocean eddies are not perturbations on an energetic mean flow.
[src:ocean-modeling/ocean-general-circulation-model] They may play an important role in the poleward transport of heat.
[src:ocean-modeling/ocean-general-circulation-model] Second, they are relatively small in horizontal extent so that ocean climate models, which must have the same overall exterior dimensions as AGCMs, may require as much as 20 times the resolution as AGCM if the eddies are to be explicitly resolved.
[src:ocean-modeling/ocean-general-circulation-model] There also are more constraints on the OGCM's due to lacking data for the ocean.
[src:ocean-modeling/ocean-general-circulation-model] The bottom topography is especially lacking.
[src:ocean-modeling/ocean-general-circulation-model] Large swaths of the ocean are not mapped in high detail.
[src:ocean-modeling/ocean-general-circulation-model] This is in stark contrast to the land topography which can be mapped in detail by satellite altimeters.
[src:ocean-modeling/ocean-general-circulation-model] This creates even bigger uncertainties in the boundary conditions.
[src:ocean-modeling/ocean-general-circulation-model] Secondly, the atmosphere only has a changing geometry for the lower levels for most of its extent.
[src:ocean-modeling/ocean-general-circulation-model] While the ocean has sharp boundaries, with large swaths of land as complex boundary conditions.
[src:ocean-modeling/ocean-general-circulation-model] The relation between paleoclimate and the effect on the ocean circulation has been widely studied.
[src:ocean-modeling/ocean-general-circulation-model] The first attempts at doing this often used the present-day forcings extrapolated to the past climate from proxies.
[src:ocean-modeling/ocean-general-circulation-model] The closure of the different passages in the ocean can then be simulated by simply blocking them with a thin line in the bathymetry.
[src:ocean-modeling/ocean-general-circulation-model] For instance closing the present-day Drake Passage.
[src:ocean-modeling/ocean-general-circulation-model] These days, more complicated paleo bathymetries are used along with better proxies.
[src:ocean-modeling/ocean-general-circulation-model] To test the quality of the models, the Paleoclimate Modelling Intercomparison Project has been established.
[src:ocean-modeling/ocean-general-circulation-model] We can classify ocean models according to different standards.
[src:ocean-modeling/ocean-general-circulation-model] For example, according to vertical ordinates we have geo-potential, isopycnal and topography-following models.
[src:ocean-modeling/ocean-general-circulation-model] According to horizontal discretizations we have unstaggered or staggered grids.
[src:ocean-modeling/ocean-general-circulation-model] According to methods of approximation we have finite difference and finite element models.
[src:ocean-modeling/ocean-general-circulation-model] Basin-scale models: To compare OGCM results with observations we need realistic basin information instead of idealized data.
[src:ocean-modeling/ocean-general-circulation-model] However, if we only pay attention to local observation data, we don't need to run whole global simulation, and by doing that we can save a lot of computational resources.
[src:ocean-modeling/ocean-general-circulation-model] Global models: This kind of model is the most computationally costly one.
[src:ocean-modeling/ocean-general-circulation-model] More experiments are needed as a preliminary step in constructing coupled Earth system models.
[src:ocean-modeling/physical-oceanography] Physical oceanography is one of several sub-domains into which oceanography is divided.
[src:ocean-modeling/physical-oceanography] Others include biological, chemical and geological oceanography.
[src:ocean-modeling/physical-oceanography] Like the study of atmospheric physics, physical oceanography is founded upon principles of thermodynamics and fluid mechanics.
[src:ocean-modeling/physical-oceanography] Physical oceanography may be subdivided into *descriptive* and *dynamical* physical oceanography.
[src:ocean-modeling/physical-oceanography] Descriptive physical oceanography seeks to research the ocean through observations and complex numerical models that describe temperature, salinity, density, currents and other ocean features as accurately and completely as possible.
[src:ocean-modeling/physical-oceanography] Dynamical physical oceanography focuses primarily upon the processes that govern the motion of fluids with emphasis upon theoretical research and numerical models.
[src:ocean-modeling/physical-oceanography] These are part of the large field of Geophysical Fluid Dynamics (GFD) that is shared together with meteorology.
[src:ocean-modeling/physical-oceanography] GFD is a sub field of fluid dynamics describing flows occurring on spatial and temporal scales that are greatly influenced by the Coriolis force.
[src:ocean-modeling/physical-oceanography] Roughly 100% of the planet's water is in its oceans, and the oceans are the source of the vast majority of water vapor that condenses in the atmosphere and falls as rain or snow on the continents.
[src:ocean-modeling/physical-oceanography] The tremendous heat capacity of the oceans moderates the planet's climate, and its absorption of various gases affects the composition of the atmosphere.
[src:ocean-modeling/physical-oceanography] The ocean's influence extends even to the composition of volcanic rocks through seafloor metamorphism, as well as to that of volcanic gases and magmas created at subduction zones.
[src:ocean-modeling/physical-oceanography] From sea level, the oceans are far deeper than the continents are tall; examination of the Earth's hypsographic curve shows that the average elevation of Earth's landmasses is only 840 metres (2,760 ft), while the ocean's average depth is 3,800 metres (12,500 ft).
[src:ocean-modeling/physical-oceanography] Though this apparent discrepancy is great, for both land and sea, the respective extremes such as mountains and trenches are rare.
[src:ocean-modeling/physical-oceanography] Because the vast majority of the world ocean's volume is deep water, the mean temperature of seawater is low; roughly 75% of the ocean's volume has a temperature from 0° – 5 °C (Pinet 1996).
[src:ocean-modeling/physical-oceanography] The same percentage falls in a salinity range between 34 and 35 ppt (3.4–3.5%) (Pinet 1996).
[src:ocean-modeling/physical-oceanography] There is still quite a bit of variation, however.
[src:ocean-modeling/physical-oceanography] Surface temperatures can range from below freezing near the poles to 35 °C in restricted tropical seas, while salinity can vary from 10 to 41 ppt (1.0–4.1%).
[src:ocean-modeling/physical-oceanography] The vertical structure of the temperature can be divided into three basic layers, a surface mixed layer, where gradients are low, a thermocline where gradients are high, and a poorly stratified abyss.
[src:ocean-modeling/physical-oceanography] In terms of temperature, the ocean's layers are highly latitude-dependent; the thermocline is pronounced in the tropics, but nonexistent in polar waters (Marshak 2001).
[src:ocean-modeling/physical-oceanography] The halocline usually lies near the surface, where evaporation raises salinity in the tropics, or meltwater dilutes it in polar regions.
[src:ocean-modeling/physical-oceanography] These variations of salinity and temperature with depth change the density of the seawater, creating the pycnocline.
[src:ocean-modeling/physical-oceanography] The temperature of ocean water varies significantly across different regions and depths.
[src:ocean-modeling/physical-oceanography] As mentioned, the vast majority of ocean water (around 75%) lies between 0° and 5°C, mostly in the deep ocean, where sunlight does not penetrate.
[src:ocean-modeling/physical-oceanography] The surface layers, however, experience far greater variability.
[src:ocean-modeling/physical-oceanography] In polar regions, surface temperatures can drop below freezing, while in tropical and subtropical regions, they may reach up to 35°C.
[src:ocean-modeling/physical-oceanography] This thermal stratification results in a vertical temperature gradient that divides the ocean into distinct layers.
[src:ocean-modeling/physical-oceanography] **Thermocline**: Below the mixed layer lies the thermocline, a zone where temperature decreases rapidly with increasing depth.
[src:ocean-modeling/physical-oceanography] The thermocline is especially pronounced in tropical and temperate regions but is absent in polar waters where surface temperatures are already near freezing.
[src:ocean-modeling/physical-oceanography] The depth and sharpness of the thermocline can shift with seasonal changes and ocean currents, playing a critical role in regulating heat exchange between the ocean and the atmosphere.
[src:ocean-modeling/physical-oceanography] **Abyssal Zone**: Beneath the thermocline is the deep ocean or abyssal zone, where temperatures remain relatively uniform, hovering just above freezing (0°-3°C).
[src:ocean-modeling/physical-oceanography] This cold, dense water originates from polar regions, where surface water cools, sinks, and spreads towards the equator along the ocean floor, forming the deep ocean circulation system.
[src:ocean-modeling/physical-oceanography] Salinity, a measure of the concentration of dissolved salts in seawater, typically ranges between 34 and 35 parts per thousand (ppt) in most of the world’s oceans.
[src:ocean-modeling/physical-oceanography] However, localized factors such as evaporation, precipitation, river runoff, and ice formation or melting cause significant variations in salinity.
[src:ocean-modeling/physical-oceanography] These variations are often most evident in coastal areas and marginal seas.
[src:ocean-modeling/physical-oceanography] **Halocline**: The halocline is a layer within the ocean where salinity changes rapidly with depth.
[src:ocean-modeling/physical-oceanography] This stratification can be influenced by surface processes like evaporation (which increases salinity) and freshwater input (which decreases it).
[src:ocean-modeling/physical-oceanography] The halocline often coincides with the thermocline, particularly in tropical and subtropical regions, contributing to overall water column stability.
[src:ocean-modeling/physical-oceanography] **Polar Regions**: In polar areas, surface salinity is generally lower due to freshwater input from melting ice.
[src:ocean-modeling/physical-oceanography] During sea ice formation, however, brine rejection increases the salinity of surrounding waters, contributing to the sinking of dense water masses and the formation of deep ocean currents that drive global circulation patterns.
[src:ocean-modeling/physical-oceanography] The salt in the oceans originates from runoff from terrestrial sources as well as hydrothermal vents.
[src:ocean-modeling/physical-oceanography] It has been estimated that the salinity of oceans was greater in the distant past than it is today.
[src:ocean-modeling/physical-oceanography] The combination of temperature and salinity variations leads to changes in seawater density.
[src:ocean-modeling/physical-oceanography] Seawater density is primarily influenced by both these factors—colder, saltier water is denser than warmer, fresher water.
[src:ocean-modeling/physical-oceanography] This variation in density creates stratification in the ocean and is key to understanding ocean circulation patterns.
[src:ocean-modeling/physical-oceanography] **Thermohaline Circulation**: Density differences drive the thermohaline circulation, also known as the global "conveyor belt," which plays a crucial role in regulating Earth's climate.
[src:ocean-modeling/physical-oceanography] Cold, dense water formed in the polar regions sinks and moves along the ocean floor toward the equator, while warmer surface waters flow poleward to replace it.
[src:ocean-modeling/physical-oceanography] This global circulation helps redistribute heat and maintains the ocean's dynamic equilibrium.
[src:ocean-modeling/physical-oceanography] **Regional Variations**: In areas of upwelling or downwelling, the density structure of the water column can be disrupted.
[src:ocean-modeling/physical-oceanography] Upwelling brings cooler, nutrient-rich water to the surface, while downwelling pushes surface waters to greater depths, impacting local ecosystems and global climate.
[src:ocean-modeling/physical-oceanography] Understanding the complex interactions between temperature, salinity, and density is essential for predicting ocean circulation patterns, climate change effects, and the health of marine ecosystems.
[src:ocean-modeling/physical-oceanography] These factors also influence marine life, as many species are sensitive to the specific temperature and salinity ranges of their habitats.
[src:ocean-modeling/physical-oceanography] Energy for the ocean circulation (and for the atmospheric circulation) comes from solar radiation and gravitational energy from the Sun and Moon.
[src:ocean-modeling/physical-oceanography] Perhaps three quarters of this heat is carried in the atmosphere; the rest is carried in the ocean.
[src:ocean-modeling/physical-oceanography] The atmosphere is heated from below, which leads to convection, the largest expression of which is the Hadley circulation.
[src:ocean-modeling/physical-oceanography] By contrast the ocean is heated from above, which tends to suppress convection.
[src:ocean-modeling/physical-oceanography] Instead ocean deep water is formed in polar regions where cold salty waters sink in fairly restricted areas.
[src:ocean-modeling/physical-oceanography] This is the beginning of the thermohaline circulation.
[src:ocean-modeling/physical-oceanography] Oceanic currents are largely driven by the surface wind stress; hence the large-scale atmospheric circulation is important to understanding the ocean circulation.
[src:ocean-modeling/physical-oceanography] The Hadley circulation leads to Easterly winds in the tropics and Westerlies in mid-latitudes.
[src:ocean-modeling/physical-oceanography] This leads to slow equatorward flow throughout most of a subtropical ocean basin (the Sverdrup balance).
[src:ocean-modeling/physical-oceanography] The return flow occurs in an intense, narrow, poleward western boundary current.
[src:ocean-modeling/physical-oceanography] Like the atmosphere, the ocean is far wider than it is deep, and hence horizontal motion is in general much faster than vertical motion.
[src:ocean-modeling/physical-oceanography] In the southern hemisphere there is a continuous belt of ocean, and hence the mid-latitude westerlies force the strong Antarctic Circumpolar Current.
[src:ocean-modeling/physical-oceanography] In the northern hemisphere the land masses prevent this and the ocean circulation is broken into smaller gyres in the Atlantic and Pacific basins.
[src:ocean-modeling/physical-oceanography] The Coriolis effect results in a deflection of fluid flows (to the right in the Northern Hemisphere and left in the Southern Hemisphere).
[src:ocean-modeling/physical-oceanography] This has profound effects on the flow of the oceans.
[src:ocean-modeling/physical-oceanography] In particular it means the flow goes *around* high and low pressure systems, permitting them to persist for long periods of time.
[src:ocean-modeling/physical-oceanography] As a result, tiny variations in pressure can produce measurable currents.
[src:ocean-modeling/physical-oceanography] A slope of one part in one million in sea surface height, for example, will result in a current of 10 cm/s at mid-latitudes.
[src:ocean-modeling/physical-oceanography] The fact that the Coriolis effect is largest at the poles and weak at the equator results in sharp, relatively steady western boundary currents which are absent on eastern boundaries.
[src:ocean-modeling/physical-oceanography] Ekman transport results in the net transport of surface water 90 degrees to the right of the wind in the Northern Hemisphere, and 90 degrees to the left of the wind in the Southern Hemisphere.
[src:ocean-modeling/physical-oceanography] As the wind blows across the surface of the ocean, it "grabs" onto a thin layer of the surface water.
[src:ocean-modeling/physical-oceanography] In turn, that thin sheet of water transfers motion energy to the thin layer of water under it, and so on.
[src:ocean-modeling/physical-oceanography] However, because of the Coriolis Effect, the direction of travel of the layers of water slowly move farther and farther to the right as they get deeper in the Northern Hemisphere, and to the left in the Southern Hemisphere.
[src:ocean-modeling/physical-oceanography] In most cases, the very bottom layer of water affected by the wind is at a depth of 100 m – 150 m and is traveling about 180 degrees, completely opposite of the direction that the wind is blowing.
[src:ocean-modeling/physical-oceanography] Overall, the net transport of water would be 90 degrees from the original direction of the wind.
[src:ocean-modeling/physical-oceanography] Langmuir circulation results in the occurrence of thin, visible stripes, called windrows on the surface of the ocean parallel to the direction that the wind is blowing.
[src:ocean-modeling/physical-oceanography] If the wind is blowing with more than 3 m s−1, it can create parallel windrows alternating upwelling and downwelling about 5–300 m apart.
[src:ocean-modeling/physical-oceanography] These windrows are created by adjacent ovular water cells (extending to about 6 m (20 ft) deep) alternating rotating clockwise and counterclockwise.
[src:ocean-modeling/physical-oceanography] In the convergence zones debris, foam and seaweed accumulates, while at the divergence zones plankton are caught and carried to the surface.
[src:ocean-modeling/physical-oceanography] If there are many plankton in the divergence zone fish are often attracted to feed on them.
[src:ocean-modeling/physical-oceanography] At the ocean-atmosphere interface, the ocean and atmosphere exchange fluxes of heat, moisture and momentum.
[src:ocean-modeling/physical-oceanography] The important heat terms at the surface are the sensible heat flux, the latent heat flux, the incoming solar radiation and the balance of long-wave (infrared) radiation.
[src:ocean-modeling/physical-oceanography] In general, the tropical oceans will tend to show a net gain of heat, and the polar oceans a net loss, the result of a net transfer of energy polewards in the oceans.
[src:ocean-modeling/physical-oceanography] The oceans' large heat capacity moderates the climate of areas adjacent to the oceans, leading to a maritime climate at such locations.
[src:ocean-modeling/physical-oceanography] This can be a result of heat storage in summer and release in winter; or of transport of heat from warmer locations: a particularly notable example of this is Western Europe, which is heated at least in part by the north Atlantic drift.
[src:ocean-modeling/physical-oceanography] Surface winds tend to be of order meters per second; ocean currents of order centimeters per second.
[src:ocean-modeling/physical-oceanography] Hence from the point of view of the atmosphere, the ocean can be considered effectively stationary; from the point of view of the ocean, the atmosphere imposes a significant wind stress on its surface, and this forces large-scale currents in the ocean.
[src:ocean-modeling/physical-oceanography] Through the wind stress, the wind generates ocean surface waves; the longer waves have a phase velocity tending towards the wind speed.
[src:ocean-modeling/physical-oceanography] Momentum of the surface winds is transferred into the energy flux by the ocean surface waves.
[src:ocean-modeling/physical-oceanography] The increased roughness of the ocean surface, by the presence of the waves, changes the wind near the surface.
[src:ocean-modeling/physical-oceanography] The ocean can gain moisture from rainfall, or lose it through evaporation.
[src:ocean-modeling/physical-oceanography] Evaporative loss leaves the ocean saltier; the Mediterranean and Persian Gulf for example have strong evaporative loss; the resulting plume of dense salty water may be traced through the Straits of Gibraltar into the Atlantic Ocean.
[src:ocean-modeling/physical-oceanography] At one time, it was believed that evaporation/precipitation was a major driver of ocean currents; it is now known to be only a very minor factor.
[src:ocean-modeling/physical-oceanography] A Kelvin wave is any progressive wave that is channeled between two boundaries or opposing forces (usually between the Coriolis force and a coastline or the equator).
[src:ocean-modeling/physical-oceanography] There are two types, coastal and equatorial.
[src:ocean-modeling/physical-oceanography] Kelvin waves are gravity driven and non-dispersive.
[src:ocean-modeling/physical-oceanography] This means that Kelvin waves can retain their shape and direction over long periods of time.
[src:ocean-modeling/physical-oceanography] They are usually created by a sudden shift in the wind, such as the change of the trade winds at the beginning of the El Niño-Southern Oscillation.
[src:ocean-modeling/physical-oceanography] Coastal Kelvin waves follow shorelines and will always propagate in a counterclockwise direction in the Northern Hemisphere (with the shoreline to the right of the direction of travel) and clockwise in the Southern Hemisphere.
[src:ocean-modeling/physical-oceanography] Equatorial Kelvin waves propagate to the east in both the Northern Hemisphere and Southern Hemisphere, using the equator as a guide.
[src:ocean-modeling/physical-oceanography] Kelvin waves are known to have very high speeds, typically around 2–3 meters per second.
[src:ocean-modeling/physical-oceanography] They have wavelengths of thousands of kilometers and amplitudes in the tens of meters.
[src:ocean-modeling/physical-oceanography] Rossby waves, or planetary waves are huge, slow waves generated in the troposphere by temperature differences between the ocean and the continents.
[src:ocean-modeling/physical-oceanography] Their major restoring force is the change in Coriolis force with latitude.
[src:ocean-modeling/physical-oceanography] Their wave amplitudes are usually in the tens of meters and very large wavelengths.
[src:ocean-modeling/physical-oceanography] They are usually found at low or mid latitudes.
[src:ocean-modeling/physical-oceanography] There are two types of Rossby waves, barotropic and baroclinic.
[src:ocean-modeling/physical-oceanography] Barotropic Rossby waves have the highest speeds and do not vary vertically.
[src:ocean-modeling/physical-oceanography] Baroclinic Rossby waves are much slower.
[src:ocean-modeling/physical-oceanography] The special identifying feature of Rossby waves is that the phase velocity of each individual wave always has a westward component, but the group velocity can be in any direction.
[src:ocean-modeling/physical-oceanography] Usually the shorter Rossby waves have an eastward group velocity and the longer ones have a westward group velocity.
[src:ocean-modeling/physical-oceanography] The interaction of ocean circulation, which serves as a type of heat pump, and biological effects such as the concentration of carbon dioxide can result in global climate changes on a time scale of decades.
[src:ocean-modeling/physical-oceanography] Known climate oscillations resulting from these interactions, include the Pacific decadal oscillation, North Atlantic oscillation, and Arctic oscillation.
[src:ocean-modeling/physical-oceanography] The oceanic process of thermohaline circulation is a significant component of heat redistribution across the globe, and changes in this circulation can have major impacts upon the climate.
[src:ocean-modeling/physical-oceanography] This is a coupled ocean/atmosphere wave that circles the Southern Ocean about every eight years.
[src:ocean-modeling/physical-oceanography] Since it is a wave-2 phenomenon (there are two peaks and two troughs in a latitude circle) at each fixed point in space a signal with a period of four years is seen.
[src:ocean-modeling/physical-oceanography] The wave moves eastward in the direction of the Antarctic Circumpolar Current.
[src:ocean-modeling/physical-oceanography] The ocean body surrounding the Antarctic is currently the only continuous body of water where there is a wide latitude band of open water.
[src:ocean-modeling/physical-oceanography] It interconnects the Atlantic, Pacific and Indian oceans, and provide an uninterrupted stretch for the prevailing westerly winds to significantly increase wave amplitudes.
[src:ocean-modeling/physical-oceanography] It is generally accepted that these prevailing winds are primarily responsible for the circumpolar current transport.
[src:ocean-modeling/physical-oceanography] This current is now thought to vary with time, possibly in an oscillatory manner.
[src:ocean-modeling/physical-oceanography] In the Norwegian Sea evaporative cooling is predominant, and the sinking water mass, the North Atlantic Deep Water (NADW), fills the basin and spills southwards through crevasses in the submarine sills that connect Greenland, Iceland and Britain.
[src:ocean-modeling/physical-oceanography] It then flows along the western boundary of the Atlantic with some part of the flow moving eastward along the equator and then poleward into the ocean basins.
[src:ocean-modeling/physical-oceanography] The NADW is entrained into the Circumpolar Current, and can be traced into the Indian and Pacific basins.
[src:ocean-modeling/physical-oceanography] Flow from the Arctic Ocean Basin into the Pacific, however, is blocked by the narrow shallows of the Bering Strait.
[src:ocean-modeling/physical-oceanography] Also see **marine geology** about that explores the geology of the ocean floor including plate tectonics that create deep ocean trenches.
[src:ocean-modeling/physical-oceanography] An idealised subtropical ocean basin forced by winds circling around a high pressure (anticyclonic) systems such as the Azores-Bermuda high develops a gyre circulation with slow steady flows towards the equator in the interior.
[src:ocean-modeling/physical-oceanography] As discussed by Henry Stommel, these flows are balanced in the region of the western boundary, where a thin fast polewards flow called a western boundary current develops.
[src:ocean-modeling/physical-oceanography] Flow in the real ocean is more complex, but the Gulf Stream, Agulhas and Kuroshio are examples of such currents.
[src:ocean-modeling/physical-oceanography] They are narrow (approximately 100 km across) and fast (approximately 1.5 m/s).
[src:ocean-modeling/physical-oceanography] Equatorwards western boundary currents occur in tropical and polar locations, e.g. the East Greenland and Labrador currents, in the Atlantic and the Oyashio.
[src:ocean-modeling/physical-oceanography] They are forced by winds circulation around low pressure (cyclonic).
[src:ocean-modeling/physical-oceanography] The Kuroshio Current is an ocean current found in the western Pacific Ocean off the east coast of Taiwan and flowing northeastward past Japan, where it merges with the easterly drift of the North Pacific Current.
[src:ocean-modeling/physical-oceanography] It is analogous to the Gulf Stream in the Atlantic Ocean, transporting warm, tropical water northward towards the polar region.
[src:ocean-modeling/physical-oceanography] Ocean heat flux is a turbulent and complex system which utilizes atmospheric measurement techniques such as eddy covariance to measure the rate of heat transfer expressed in the unit of or petawatts.
[src:ocean-modeling/physical-oceanography] Heat flux is the flow of energy per unit of area per unit of time.
[src:ocean-modeling/physical-oceanography] Most of the Earth's heat storage is within its seas with smaller fractions of the heat transfer in processes such as evaporation, radiation, diffusion, or absorption into the sea floor.
[src:ocean-modeling/physical-oceanography] The majority of the ocean heat flux is through advection or the movement of the ocean's currents.
[src:ocean-modeling/physical-oceanography] For example, the majority of the warm water movement in the south Atlantic is thought to have originated in the Indian Ocean.
[src:ocean-modeling/physical-oceanography] Another example of advection is the nonequatorial Pacific heating which results from subsurface processes related to atmospheric anticlines.
[src:ocean-modeling/physical-oceanography] Recent warming observations of Antarctic bottom water in the Southern Ocean is of concern to ocean scientists because bottom water changes will effect currents, nutrients, and biota elsewhere.
[src:ocean-modeling/physical-oceanography] The international awareness of global warming has focused scientific research on this topic since the 1988 creation of the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change.
[src:ocean-modeling/physical-oceanography] Improved ocean observation, instrumentation, theory, and funding has increased scientific reporting on regional and global issues related to heat.
[src:ocean-modeling/physical-oceanography] Tide gauges and satellite altimetry suggest an increase in sea level of 1.5–3 mm/yr over the past 100 years.
[src:ocean-modeling/physical-oceanography] The IPCC predicts that by 2081–2100, global warming will lead to a sea level rise of 260 to 820 mm.
[src:ocean-modeling/physical-oceanography] The rise and fall of the oceans due to tidal effects is a key influence upon the coastal areas.
[src:ocean-modeling/physical-oceanography] Ocean tides on the planet Earth are created by the gravitational effects of the Sun and Moon.
[src:ocean-modeling/physical-oceanography] The tides produced by these two bodies are roughly comparable in magnitude, but the orbital motion of the Moon results in tidal patterns that vary over the course of a month.
[src:ocean-modeling/physical-oceanography] The ebb and flow of the tides produce a cyclical current along the coast, and the strength of this current can be quite dramatic along narrow estuaries.
[src:ocean-modeling/physical-oceanography] Incoming tides can also produce a tidal bore along a river or narrow bay as the water flow against the current results in a wave on the surface.
[src:ocean-modeling/physical-oceanography] As the surface tide oscillates over topography, such as submerged seamounts or ridges, it generates internal waves at the tidal frequency, which are known as internal tides.
[src:ocean-modeling/physical-oceanography] A series of surface waves can be generated due to large-scale displacement of the ocean water.
[src:ocean-modeling/physical-oceanography] These can be caused by sub-marine landslides, seafloor deformations due to earthquakes, or the impact of a large meteorite.
[src:ocean-modeling/physical-oceanography] The waves can travel with a velocity of up to several hundred km/hour across the ocean surface, but in mid-ocean they are barely detectable with wavelengths spanning hundreds of kilometers.
[src:ocean-modeling/physical-oceanography] Tsunamis, originally called tidal waves, were renamed because they are not related to the tides.
[src:ocean-modeling/physical-oceanography] They are regarded as shallow-water waves, or waves in water with a depth less than 1/20 their wavelength.
[src:ocean-modeling/physical-oceanography] Tsunamis have very large periods, high speeds, and great wave heights.
[src:ocean-modeling/physical-oceanography] The primary impact of these waves is along the coastal shoreline, as large amounts of ocean water are cyclically propelled inland and then drawn out to sea.
[src:ocean-modeling/physical-oceanography] This can result in significant modifications to the coastline regions where the waves strike with sufficient energy.
[src:ocean-modeling/physical-oceanography] The tsunami that occurred in Lituya Bay, Alaska on July 9, 1958 was 520 m (1,710 ft) high and is the biggest tsunami ever measured, almost 90 m (300 ft) taller than the Sears Tower in Chicago and about 110 m (360 ft) taller than the former World Trade Center in New York.
[src:ocean-modeling/physical-oceanography] The wind generates ocean surface waves, which have a large impact on offshore structures, ships, Coastal erosion and sedimentation, as well as harbours.
[src:ocean-modeling/physical-oceanography] After their generation by the wind, ocean surface waves can travel (as swell) over long distances.
[src:ocean-modeling/sea-surface-temperature] Warm sea surface temperatures can develop and strengthen cyclones over the ocean.
[src:ocean-modeling/sea-surface-temperature] Tropical cyclones can also cause a cool wake.
[src:ocean-modeling/sea-surface-temperature] This is due to turbulent mixing of the upper 30 metres (100 ft) of the ocean.
[src:ocean-modeling/sea-surface-temperature] Sea surface temperature changes during the day.
[src:ocean-modeling/sea-surface-temperature] This is like the air above it, but to a lesser degree.
[src:ocean-modeling/sea-surface-temperature] There is less variation in sea surface temperature on breezy days than on calm days.
[src:ocean-modeling/sea-surface-temperature] Coastal sea surface temperatures can cause offshore winds to generate upwelling, which can significantly cool or warm nearby landmasses, but shallower waters over a continental shelf are often warmer.
[src:ocean-modeling/sea-surface-temperature] Onshore winds can cause a considerable warm-up even in areas where upwelling is fairly constant, such as the northwest coast of South America.
[src:ocean-modeling/sea-surface-temperature] Coastal sea surface temperature values are important within numerical weather prediction as the sea surface temperature influences the atmosphere above, such as in the formation of sea breezes and sea fog.
[src:ocean-modeling/sea-surface-temperature] It is very likely that global mean sea surface temperature increased by 0.88 °C between 1850–1900 and 2011–2020 due to global warming, with most of that warming (0.60 °C) occurring between 1980 and 2020.
[src:ocean-modeling/sea-surface-temperature] The temperatures over land are rising faster than ocean temperatures.
[src:ocean-modeling/sea-surface-temperature] This is because the ocean absorbs about 90% of excess heat generated by climate change.
[src:ocean-modeling/sea-surface-temperature] Sea surface temperature (SST), or ocean surface temperature, is the water temperature close to the ocean's surface.
[src:ocean-modeling/sea-surface-temperature] The exact meaning of *surface* varies according to the measurement method used, but it is between 1 millimetre (0.04 in) and 20 metres (70 ft) below the sea surface.
[src:ocean-modeling/sea-surface-temperature] For comparison, the sea surface skin temperature relates to the top 20 or so micrometres of the ocean's surface.
[src:ocean-modeling/sea-surface-temperature] The temperature further below that is called *ocean temperature* or *deeper ocean temperature*.
[src:ocean-modeling/sea-surface-temperature] Ocean temperatures (more than 20 metres below the surface) also vary by region and time, and they contribute to variations in ocean heat content and ocean stratification.
[src:ocean-modeling/sea-surface-temperature] The increase of both ocean surface temperature and deeper ocean temperature is an important effect of climate change on oceans.
[src:ocean-modeling/sea-surface-temperature] The extent of the *ocean surface* down into the ocean is influenced by the amount of mixing that takes place between the surface water and the deeper water.
[src:ocean-modeling/sea-surface-temperature] This depends on the temperature: in the tropics the warm surface layer of about 100 m is quite stable and does not mix much with deeper water, while near the poles winter cooling and storms makes the surface layer denser and it mixes to great depth and then stratifies again in summer.
[src:ocean-modeling/sea-surface-temperature] This is why there is no simple single depth for *ocean surface*.
[src:ocean-modeling/sea-surface-temperature] The photic depth of the ocean is typically about 100 m and is related to this heated surface layer.
[src:ocean-modeling/sea-surface-temperature] It can be up to around 200 m deep in the open ocean.
[src:ocean-modeling/sea-surface-temperature] The sea surface temperature (SST) has a diurnal range, just like the Earth's atmosphere above, though to a lesser degree due to its greater thermal inertia.
[src:ocean-modeling/sea-surface-temperature] On calm days, the temperature can vary by 6 °C (10 °F).
[src:ocean-modeling/sea-surface-temperature] The temperature of the ocean at depth lags the Earth's atmosphere temperature by 15 days per 10 metres (33 ft), which means for locations like the Aral Sea, temperatures near its bottom reach a maximum in December and a minimum in May and June.
[src:ocean-modeling/sea-surface-temperature] Near the coastline, some offshore and longshore winds move the warm waters near the surface offshore, and replace them with cooler water from below in the process known as Ekman transport.
[src:ocean-modeling/sea-surface-temperature] This pattern generally increases nutrients for marine life in the region, and can have a profound effect in some regions where the bottom waters are particularly nutrient-rich.
[src:ocean-modeling/sea-surface-temperature] Offshore of river deltas, freshwater flows over the top of the denser seawater, which allows it to heat faster due to limited vertical mixing.
[src:ocean-modeling/sea-surface-temperature] Remotely sensed SST can be used to detect the surface temperature signature due to tropical cyclones.
[src:ocean-modeling/sea-surface-temperature] In general, an SST cooling is observed after the passing of a hurricane, primarily as the result of mixed layer deepening and surface heat losses.
[src:ocean-modeling/sea-surface-temperature] In the wake of several day long Saharan dust outbreaks across the adjacent northern Atlantic Ocean, sea surface temperatures are reduced 0.2 C to 0.4 C (0.3 to 0.7 F).
[src:ocean-modeling/sea-surface-temperature] Other sources of short-term SST fluctuation include extratropical cyclones, rapid influxes of glacial fresh water and concentrated phytoplankton blooms due to seasonal cycles or agricultural run-off.
[src:ocean-modeling/sea-surface-temperature] The tropical ocean has been warming faster than other regions since 1950, with the greatest rates of warming in the tropical Indian Ocean, western Pacific Ocean, and western boundary currents of the subtropical gyres.
[src:ocean-modeling/sea-surface-temperature] However, the eastern Pacific Ocean, subtropical North Atlantic Ocean, and Southern Ocean have warmed more slowly than the global average or have experienced cooling since the 1950s.
[src:ocean-modeling/sea-surface-temperature] Ocean currents, such as the Atlantic Multidecadal Oscillation, can affect sea surface temperatures over several decades.
[src:ocean-modeling/sea-surface-temperature] The Atlantic Multidecadal Oscillation (AMO) is an important driver of North Atlantic SST and Northern Hemisphere climate, but the mechanisms controlling AMO variability remain poorly understood.
[src:ocean-modeling/sea-surface-temperature] Atmospheric internal variability, changes in ocean circulation, or anthropogenic drivers may control the multidecadal temperature variability associated with AMO.
[src:ocean-modeling/sea-surface-temperature] These changes in North Atlantic SST may influence winds in the subtropical North Pacific and produce warmer SSTs in the western Pacific Ocean.
[src:ocean-modeling/sea-surface-temperature] El Niño is defined by prolonged differences in Pacific Ocean surface temperatures when compared with the average value.
[src:ocean-modeling/sea-surface-temperature] The accepted definition is a warming or cooling of at least 0.5 °C (0.9 °F) averaged over the east-central tropical Pacific Ocean.
[src:ocean-modeling/sea-surface-temperature] Typically, this anomaly happens at irregular intervals of 2–7 years and lasts nine months to two years.
[src:ocean-modeling/sea-surface-temperature] When this warming or cooling occurs for only seven to nine months, it is classified as El Niño/La Niña "conditions"; when it occurs for more than that period, it is classified as El Niño/La Niña "episodes".
[src:ocean-modeling/sea-surface-temperature] The sign of an El Niño in the sea surface temperature pattern is when warm water spreads from the west Pacific and the Indian Ocean to the east Pacific.
[src:ocean-modeling/sea-surface-temperature] It takes the rain with it, causing extensive drought in the western Pacific and rainfall in the normally dry eastern Pacific.
[src:ocean-modeling/sea-surface-temperature] El Niño's warm rush of nutrient-poor tropical water, heated by its eastward passage in the Equatorial Current, replaces the cold, nutrient-rich surface water of the Humboldt Current.
[src:ocean-modeling/sea-surface-temperature] When El Niño conditions last for many months, extensive ocean warming and the reduction in Easterly Trade winds limits upwelling of cold nutrient-rich deep water and its economic impact to local fishing for an international market can be serious.
[src:ocean-modeling/sea-surface-temperature] Overall, scientists project that all regions of the oceans will warm by 2050, but models disagree for SST changes expected in the subpolar North Atlantic, the equatorial Pacific, and the Southern Ocean.
[src:ocean-modeling/sea-surface-temperature] The future global mean SST increase for the period 1995-2014 to 2081-2100 is 0.86 °C under the most modest greenhouse gas emissions scenarios, and up to 2.89 °C under the most severe emissions scenarios.
[src:ocean-modeling/sea-surface-temperature] A study published in 2025 in *Environmental Research Letters* reported that global mean sea surface temperature increases had more than quadrupled, from 0.06 K per decade during 1985–89 to 0.27 K per decade for 2019–23.
[src:ocean-modeling/sea-surface-temperature] The researchers projected that the increase inferred over the past 40 years would likely be exceeded within the next 20 years.
[src:ocean-modeling/sea-surface-temperature] There are a variety of techniques for measuring this parameter that can potentially yield different results because different things are actually being measured.
[src:ocean-modeling/sea-surface-temperature] Away from the immediate sea surface, general temperature measurements are accompanied by a reference to the specific depth of measurement.
[src:ocean-modeling/sea-surface-temperature] Sea surface temperature measurements are confined to the top portion of the ocean, known as the near-surface layer.
[src:ocean-modeling/sea-surface-temperature] The sea surface temperature was one of the first oceanographic variables to be measured.
[src:ocean-modeling/sea-surface-temperature] Benjamin Franklin suspended a mercury thermometer from a ship while travelling between the United States and Europe in his survey of the Gulf Stream in the late eighteenth century.
[src:ocean-modeling/sea-surface-temperature] SST was later measured by dipping a thermometer into a bucket of water that was manually drawn from the sea surface.
[src:ocean-modeling/sea-surface-temperature] The first automated technique for determining SST was accomplished by measuring the temperature of water in the intake port of large ships, which was underway by 1963.
[src:ocean-modeling/sea-surface-temperature] These observations have a warm bias of around 0.6 °C (1 °F) due to the heat of the engine room.
[src:ocean-modeling/sea-surface-temperature] Fixed weather buoys measure the water temperature at a depth of 3 metres (9.8 ft).
[src:ocean-modeling/sea-surface-temperature] Measurements of SST have had inconsistencies over the last 130 years due to the way they were taken.
[src:ocean-modeling/sea-surface-temperature] In the nineteenth century, measurements were taken in a bucket off a ship.
[src:ocean-modeling/sea-surface-temperature] However, there was a slight variation in temperature because of the differences in buckets.
[src:ocean-modeling/sea-surface-temperature] Samples were collected in either a wood or an uninsulated canvas bucket, but the canvas bucket cooled quicker than the wood bucket.
[src:ocean-modeling/sea-surface-temperature] The sudden change in temperature between 1940 and 1941 was the result of an undocumented change in procedure.
[src:ocean-modeling/sea-surface-temperature] The samples were taken near the engine intake because it was too dangerous to use lights to take measurements over the side of the ship at night.
[src:ocean-modeling/sea-surface-temperature] Many different drifting buoys exist around the world that vary in design, and the location of reliable temperature sensors varies.
[src:ocean-modeling/sea-surface-temperature] These measurements are beamed to satellites for automated and immediate data distribution.
[src:ocean-modeling/sea-surface-temperature] A large network of coastal buoys in U.S. waters is maintained by the National Data Buoy Center (NDBC).
[src:ocean-modeling/sea-surface-temperature] Between 1985 and 1994, an extensive array of moored and drifting buoys was deployed across the equatorial Pacific Ocean designed to help monitor and predict the El Niño phenomenon.
[src:ocean-modeling/sea-surface-temperature] Weather satellites have been available to determine sea surface temperature information since 1967, with the first global composites created during 1970.
[src:ocean-modeling/sea-surface-temperature] Since 1982, satellites have been increasingly utilized to measure SST and have allowed its spatial and temporal variation to be viewed more fully.
[src:ocean-modeling/sea-surface-temperature] Satellite measurements of SST are in reasonable agreement with in situ temperature measurements.
[src:ocean-modeling/sea-surface-temperature] The satellite measurement is made by sensing the ocean radiation in two or more wavelengths within the infrared part of the electromagnetic spectrum or other parts of the spectrum which can then be empirically related to SST.
[src:ocean-modeling/sea-surface-temperature] The satellite-measured SST provides both a synoptic view of the ocean and a high frequency of repeat views, allowing the examination of basin-wide upper ocean dynamics not possible with ships or buoys.
[src:ocean-modeling/sea-surface-temperature] NASA's (National Aeronautic and Space Administration) Moderate Resolution Imaging Spectroradiometer (MODIS) SST satellites have been providing global SST data since 2000, available with a one-day lag.
[src:ocean-modeling/sea-surface-temperature] NOAA's GOES (Geostationary Orbiting Earth Satellites) Archived 2020-08-17 at the Wayback Machine satellites are geo-stationary above the Western Hemisphere which enables them to deliver SST data on an hourly basis with only a few hours of lag time.
[src:ocean-modeling/sea-surface-temperature] There are several difficulties with satellite-based absolute SST measurements.
[src:ocean-modeling/sea-surface-temperature] All these factors make it somewhat difficult to compare satellite data to measurements from buoys or shipboard methods, complicating ground truth efforts.
[src:ocean-modeling/sea-surface-temperature] Secondly, the satellite cannot look through clouds, creating a cool bias in satellite-derived SSTs within cloudy areas.
[src:ocean-modeling/sea-surface-temperature] However, passive microwave techniques can accurately measure SST and penetrate cloud cover.
[src:ocean-modeling/sea-surface-temperature] Within atmospheric sounder channels on weather satellites, which peak just above the ocean's surface, knowledge of the sea surface temperature is important to their calibration.
[src:ocean-modeling/sea-surface-temperature] Sea surface temperature affects the behavior of the Earth's atmosphere above, so their initialization into atmospheric models is important.
[src:ocean-modeling/sea-surface-temperature] While sea surface temperature is important for tropical cyclogenesis, it is also important in determining the formation of sea fog and sea breezes.
[src:ocean-modeling/sea-surface-temperature] Heat from underlying warmer waters can significantly modify an air mass over distances as short as 35 kilometres (22 mi) to 40 kilometres (25 mi).
[src:ocean-modeling/sea-surface-temperature] For example, southwest of Northern Hemisphere extratropical cyclones, curved cyclonic flow bringing cold air across relatively warm water bodies can lead to narrow lake-effect snow (or sea effect) bands.
[src:ocean-modeling/sea-surface-temperature] Those bands bring strong localized precipitation, often in the form of snow, since large water bodies such as lakes efficiently store heat that results in significant temperature differences—larger than 13 °C (23 °F)—between the water surface and the air above.
[src:ocean-modeling/sea-surface-temperature] Because of this temperature difference, warmth and moisture are transported upward, condensing into vertically oriented clouds which produce snow showers.
[src:ocean-modeling/sea-surface-temperature] The temperature decrease with height and cloud depth are directly affected by both the water temperature and the large-scale environment.
[src:ocean-modeling/sea-surface-temperature] The stronger the temperature decrease with height, the taller the clouds get, and the greater the precipitation rate becomes.
[src:ocean-modeling/sea-surface-temperature] Ocean temperature of at least 26.5°C (79.7°F) spanning through at minimum a 50-metre depth is one of the precursors needed to maintain a tropical cyclone (a type of mesocyclone).
[src:ocean-modeling/sea-surface-temperature] These warm waters are needed to maintain the warm core that fuels tropical systems.
[src:ocean-modeling/sea-surface-temperature] This value is well above 16.1 °C (60.9 °F), the long term global average surface temperature of the oceans.
[src:ocean-modeling/sea-surface-temperature] However, this requirement can be considered only a general baseline because it assumes that the ambient atmospheric environment surrounding an area of disturbed weather presents average conditions.
[src:ocean-modeling/sea-surface-temperature] Tropical cyclones have intensified when SSTs were slightly below this standard temperature.
[src:ocean-modeling/sea-surface-temperature] Tropical cyclones are known to form even when normal conditions are not met.
[src:ocean-modeling/sea-surface-temperature] For example, cooler air temperatures at a higher altitude (e.g., at the 500 hPa level, or 5.9 km) can lead to tropical cyclogenesis at lower water temperatures, as a certain lapse rate is required to force the atmosphere to be unstable enough for convection.
[src:ocean-modeling/sea-surface-temperature] In a moist atmosphere, this lapse rate is 6.5 °C/km, while in an atmosphere with less than 100% relative humidity, the required lapse rate is 9.8 °C/km.
[src:ocean-modeling/sea-surface-temperature] At the 500 hPa level, the air temperature averages −7 °C (18 °F) within the tropics, but air in the tropics is normally dry at this height, giving the air room to wet-bulb, or cool as it moistens, to a more favorable temperature that can then support convection.
[src:ocean-modeling/sea-surface-temperature] Inside a cold cyclone, 500 hPa temperatures can fall as low as −30 °C (−22 °F), which can initiate convection even in the driest atmospheres.
[src:ocean-modeling/sea-surface-temperature] This also explains why moisture in the mid-levels of the troposphere, roughly at the 500 hPa level, is normally a requirement for development.
[src:ocean-modeling/sea-surface-temperature] However, when dry air is found at the same height, temperatures at 500 hPa need to be even colder as dry atmospheres require a greater lapse rate for instability than moist atmospheres.
[src:ocean-modeling/sea-surface-temperature] At heights near the tropopause, the 30-year average temperature (as measured in the period encompassing 1961 through 1990) was −77 °C (−132 °F).
[src:ocean-modeling/sea-surface-temperature] One example of a tropical cyclone maintaining itself over cooler waters was Epsilon late in the 2005 Atlantic hurricane season.
[src:ocean-modeling/thermohaline-circulation] Wind-driven surface currents (such as the Gulf Stream) travel polewards from the equatorial Atlantic Ocean, cooling and sinking en-route to higher latitudes - eventually becoming part of the North Atlantic Deep Water - before flowing into the ocean basins.
[src:ocean-modeling/thermohaline-circulation] The water in these circuits transport energy - as heat - and mass - as dissolved solids and gases - around the globe.
[src:ocean-modeling/thermohaline-circulation] Consequently, the state of the circulation greatly impacts the climate of Earth.
[src:ocean-modeling/thermohaline-circulation] The thermohaline circulation is often referred to as the*ocean conveyor belt*, *great ocean conveyor*, or "*global conveyor belt*" - a term coined by climate scientist Wallace Smith Broecker.
[src:ocean-modeling/thermohaline-circulation] It is also known as the meridional overturning circulation, or *MOC*; a name used to signify that circulation patterns caused by temperature and salinity gradients are not necessarily part of a *single* global circulation.
[src:ocean-modeling/thermohaline-circulation] This is due, in part, to the difficulty in separating parts of the circulation driven by temperature and salinity from those affected by factors such as wind and tidal force.
[src:ocean-modeling/thermohaline-circulation] This global circulation comprises two major "limbs;" the Atlantic meridional overturning circulation (*AMOC*) centered in the north Atlantic Ocean, and the Southern Ocean overturning circulation, or *Southern Ocean meridional circulation* (*SMOC*) located near Antarctica.
[src:ocean-modeling/thermohaline-circulation] Since 90% of the human population occupies the Northern Hemisphere, more extensive research has been undertaken on the AMOC, however the SMOC is of equal importance to the global climate.
[src:ocean-modeling/thermohaline-circulation] Evidence suggests both circulations are slowing due to climate change in line with increasing rates of dilution from melting ice sheets - critically affecting the salinity of Antarctic bottom water.
[src:ocean-modeling/thermohaline-circulation] In addition, the potential for outright collapse of either circulation to a much weaker state exemplifies tipping points in the climate system.
[src:ocean-modeling/thermohaline-circulation] If either hemisphere experiences collapse of its circulation, the likelihood of prolonged dry spells and droughts would increase as precipitation decreases, while the other hemisphere will become wetter.
[src:ocean-modeling/thermohaline-circulation] Marine ecosystems are then more likely to receive fewer nutrients and experience greater ocean deoxygenation.
[src:ocean-modeling/thermohaline-circulation] In the Northern Hemisphere, the collapse of AMOC would lead to substantially lower temperatures in many European countries, while the east coast of North America is predicted to see accelerated sea level rise.
[src:ocean-modeling/thermohaline-circulation] The collapse of these circulations is generally accepted to be more than a century away, and may only occur in the event of rapid and high sea-temperature increases.
[src:ocean-modeling/thermohaline-circulation] However, these projections are marked by significant uncertainty.
[src:ocean-modeling/thermohaline-circulation] It has long been known that wind drives ocean currents, but only at the surface.
[src:ocean-modeling/thermohaline-circulation] In the 19th century, some oceanographers suggested that the convection of heat could drive deeper currents.
[src:ocean-modeling/thermohaline-circulation] In 1908, Johan Sandström performed a series of experiments at a Bornö Marine Research Station which proved that the currents driven by thermal energy transfer can exist, but require that "heating occurs at a greater depth than cooling".
[src:ocean-modeling/thermohaline-circulation] Normally, the opposite occurs, because ocean water is heated from above by the Sun and becomes less dense, so the surface layer floats on the surface above the cooler, denser layers, resulting in ocean stratification.
[src:ocean-modeling/thermohaline-circulation] However, wind and tides cause mixing between these water layers, with diapycnal mixing caused by tidal currents being one example.
[src:ocean-modeling/thermohaline-circulation] This mixing is what enables the convection between ocean layers, and thus, deep water currents.
[src:ocean-modeling/thermohaline-circulation] In the 1920s, Sandström's framework was expanded by accounting for the role of salinity in ocean layer formation.
[src:ocean-modeling/thermohaline-circulation] Salinity is important because like temperature, it affects water density.
[src:ocean-modeling/thermohaline-circulation] Water becomes less dense as its temperature increases and the distance between its molecules expands, but more dense as the salinity increases, since there is a larger mass of salts dissolved within that water.
[src:ocean-modeling/thermohaline-circulation] Further, while fresh water is at its most dense at 4 °C, seawater only gets denser as it cools, up until it reaches the freezing point.
[src:ocean-modeling/thermohaline-circulation] That freezing point is also lower than for fresh water due to salinity, and can be below −2 °C, depending on salinity and pressure.
[src:ocean-modeling/thermohaline-circulation] These density differences caused by temperature and salinity ultimately separate ocean water into distinct water masses, such as the North Atlantic Deep Water (NADW) and Antarctic Bottom Water (AABW).
[src:ocean-modeling/thermohaline-circulation] These two waters are the main drivers of the circulation, which was established in 1960 by Henry Stommel and Arnold B.
[src:ocean-modeling/thermohaline-circulation] They have chemical, temperature and isotopic ratio signatures (such as 231Pa / 230Th ratios) which can be traced, their flow rate calculated, and their age determined.
[src:ocean-modeling/thermohaline-circulation] NADW is formed because North Atlantic is a rare place in the ocean where precipitation, which adds fresh water to the ocean and so reduces its salinity, is outweighed by evaporation, in part due to high windiness.
[src:ocean-modeling/thermohaline-circulation] When water evaporates, it leaves salt behind, and so the surface waters of the North Atlantic are particularly salty.
[src:ocean-modeling/thermohaline-circulation] North Atlantic is also an already cool region, and evaporative cooling reduces water temperature even further.
[src:ocean-modeling/thermohaline-circulation] Thus, this water sinks downward in the Norwegian Sea, fills the Arctic Ocean Basin and spills southwards through the Greenland-Scotland-Ridge – crevasses in the submarine sills that connect Greenland, Iceland and Great Britain.
[src:ocean-modeling/thermohaline-circulation] It cannot flow towards the Pacific Ocean due to the narrow shallows of the Bering Strait, but it does slowly flow into the deep abyssal plains of the south Atlantic.
[src:ocean-modeling/thermohaline-circulation] In the Southern Ocean, strong katabatic winds blowing from the Antarctic continent onto the ice shelves will blow the newly formed sea ice away, opening polynyas in locations such as Weddell and Ross Seas, off the Adélie Coast and by Cape Darnley.
[src:ocean-modeling/thermohaline-circulation] The ocean, no longer protected by sea ice, suffers a brutal and strong cooling (see polynya).
[src:ocean-modeling/thermohaline-circulation] Meanwhile, sea ice starts reforming, so the surface waters also get saltier, hence very dense.
[src:ocean-modeling/thermohaline-circulation] In fact, the formation of sea ice contributes to an increase in surface seawater salinity; saltier brine is left behind as the sea ice forms around it (pure water preferentially being frozen).
[src:ocean-modeling/thermohaline-circulation] Increasing salinity lowers the freezing point of seawater, so cold liquid brine is formed in inclusions within a honeycomb of ice.
[src:ocean-modeling/thermohaline-circulation] The brine progressively melts the ice just beneath it, eventually dripping out of the ice matrix and sinking.
[src:ocean-modeling/thermohaline-circulation] This process is known as brine rejection.
[src:ocean-modeling/thermohaline-circulation] The resulting Antarctic bottom water sinks and flows north and east.
[src:ocean-modeling/thermohaline-circulation] It is denser than the NADW, and so flows beneath it.
[src:ocean-modeling/thermohaline-circulation] AABW formed in the Weddell Sea will mainly fill the Atlantic and Indian Basins, whereas the AABW formed in the Ross Sea will flow towards the Pacific Ocean.
[src:ocean-modeling/thermohaline-circulation] At the Indian Ocean, a vertical exchange of a lower layer of cold and salty water from the Atlantic and the warmer and fresher upper ocean water from the tropical Pacific occurs, in what is known as **overturning**.
[src:ocean-modeling/thermohaline-circulation] In the Pacific Ocean, the rest of the cold and salty water from the Atlantic undergoes haline forcing, and becomes warmer and fresher more quickly.
[src:ocean-modeling/thermohaline-circulation] The out-flowing undersea of cold and salty water makes the sea level of the Atlantic slightly lower than the Pacific and salinity or halinity of water at the Atlantic higher than the Pacific.
[src:ocean-modeling/thermohaline-circulation] This generates a large but slow flow of warmer and fresher upper ocean water from the tropical Pacific to the Indian Ocean through the Indonesian Archipelago to replace the cold and salty Antarctic Bottom Water.
[src:ocean-modeling/thermohaline-circulation] This is also known as 'haline forcing' (net high latitude freshwater gain and low latitude evaporation).
[src:ocean-modeling/thermohaline-circulation] This warmer, fresher water from the Pacific flows up through the South Atlantic to Greenland, where it cools off and undergoes evaporative cooling and sinks to the ocean floor, providing a continuous thermohaline circulation.
[src:ocean-modeling/thermohaline-circulation] As the deep waters sink into the ocean basins, they displace the older deep-water masses, which gradually become less dense due to continued ocean mixing.
[src:ocean-modeling/thermohaline-circulation] Thus, some water is rising, in what is known as upwelling.
[src:ocean-modeling/thermohaline-circulation] Its speeds are very slow even compared to the movement of the bottom water masses.
[src:ocean-modeling/thermohaline-circulation] It is therefore difficult to measure where upwelling occurs using current speeds, given all the other wind-driven processes going on in the surface ocean.
[src:ocean-modeling/thermohaline-circulation] Deep waters have their own chemical signature, formed from the breakdown of particulate matter falling into them over the course of their long journey at depth.
[src:ocean-modeling/thermohaline-circulation] A number of scientists have tried to use these tracers to infer where the upwelling occurs.
[src:ocean-modeling/thermohaline-circulation] Wallace Broecker, using box models, has asserted that the bulk of deep upwelling occurs in the North Pacific, using as evidence the high values of silicon found in these waters.
[src:ocean-modeling/thermohaline-circulation] Other investigators have not found such clear evidence.
[src:ocean-modeling/thermohaline-circulation] Computer models of ocean circulation increasingly place most of the deep upwelling in the Southern Ocean, associated with the strong winds in the open latitudes between South America and Antarctica.
[src:ocean-modeling/thermohaline-circulation] Direct estimates of the strength of the thermohaline circulation have also been made at 26.5°N in the North Atlantic, by the UK-US RAPID programme.
[src:ocean-modeling/thermohaline-circulation] It combines direct estimates of ocean transport using current meters and subsea cable measurements with estimates of the geostrophic current from temperature and salinity measurements to provide continuous, full-depth, basin-wide estimates of the meridional overturning circulation.
[src:ocean-modeling/thermohaline-circulation] However, it has only been operating since 2004, which is too short when the timescale of the circulation is measured in centuries.
[src:ocean-modeling/thermohaline-circulation] The thermohaline circulation plays an important role in supplying heat to the polar regions, and thus in regulating the amount of sea ice in these regions, although poleward heat transport outside the tropics is considerably larger in the atmosphere than in the ocean.
[src:ocean-modeling/thermohaline-circulation] Changes in the thermohaline circulation are thought to have significant impacts on the Earth's radiation budget.
[src:ocean-modeling/thermohaline-circulation] Large influxes of low-density meltwater from Lake Agassiz and deglaciation in North America are thought to have led to a shifting of deep water formation and subsidence in the extreme North Atlantic and caused the climate period in Europe known as the Younger Dryas.
[src:ocean-modeling/thermohaline-circulation] In 2021, the IPCC Sixth Assessment Report again said the AMOC is "very likely" to decline within the 21st century and that there was a "high confidence" changes to it would be reversible within centuries if warming was reversed.
[src:ocean-modeling/thermohaline-circulation] Unlike the Fifth Assessment Report, it had only "medium confidence" rather than "high confidence" in the AMOC avoiding a collapse before the end of the 21st century.
[src:ocean-modeling/thermohaline-circulation] This reduction in confidence was likely influenced by several review studies that draw attention to the circulation stability bias within general circulation models, and simplified ocean-modelling studies suggesting the AMOC may be more vulnerable to abrupt change than larger-scale models suggest.
[src:ocean-modeling/thermohaline-circulation] As of 2024, there is no consensus on whether a consistent slowing of the AMOC circulation has occurred but there is little doubt it will occur in the event of continued climate change.
[src:ocean-modeling/thermohaline-circulation] According to the IPCC, the most-likely effects of future AMOC decline are reduced precipitation in mid-latitudes, changing patterns of strong precipitation in the tropics and Europe, and strengthening storms that follow the North Atlantic track.
[src:ocean-modeling/thermohaline-circulation] In 2020, research found a weakened AMOC would slow the decline in Arctic sea ice and result in atmospheric trends similar to those that likely occurred during the Younger Dryas, such as a southward displacement of Intertropical Convergence Zone.
[src:ocean-modeling/thermohaline-circulation] Changes in precipitation under high-emissions scenarios would be far larger.
[src:ocean-modeling/thermohaline-circulation] A decline in the AMOC would be accompanied by an acceleration of sea level rise along the U.S.
[src:ocean-modeling/thermohaline-circulation] East Coast; at least one such event has been connected to a temporary slowing of the AMOC.
[src:ocean-modeling/thermohaline-circulation] This effect would be caused by increased warming and thermal expansion of coastal waters, which would transfer less of their heat toward Europe; it is one of the reasons sea level rise along the U.S.
[src:ocean-modeling/thermohaline-circulation] East Coast is estimated to be three-to-four times higher than the global average.
[src:ocean-modeling/thermohaline-circulation] Climate models currently disagree on whether the Southern Ocean circulation would continue to respond to changes in SAM the way it does now, or if it will eventually adjust to them.
[src:ocean-modeling/thermohaline-circulation] As of early 2020s, their best, limited-confidence estimate is that the lower cell would continue to weaken, while the upper cell may strengthen by around 20% over the 21st century.
[src:ocean-modeling/thermohaline-circulation] A key reason for the uncertainty is the poor and inconsistent representation of ocean stratification in even the CMIP6 models – the most advanced generation available as of early 2020s.
[src:ocean-modeling/thermohaline-circulation] Furthermore, the largest long-term role in the state of the circulation is played by Antarctic meltwater, and Antarctic ice loss had been the least-certain aspect of future sea level rise projections for a long time.
[src:ocean-modeling/thermohaline-circulation] Similar processes are taking place with Atlantic meridional overturning circulation (AMOC), which is also affected by the ocean warming and by meltwater flows from the declining Greenland ice sheet.
[src:ocean-modeling/thermohaline-circulation] It is possible that both circulations may not simply continue to weaken in response to increased warming and freshening, but eventually collapse to a much weaker state outright, in a way which would be difficult to reverse and constitute an example of tipping points in the climate system.
[src:ocean-modeling/thermohaline-circulation] There is paleoclimate evidence for the overturning circulation being substantially weaker than now during past periods that were both warmer and colder than now.
[src:ocean-modeling/thermohaline-circulation] However, Southern Hemisphere is only inhabited by 10% of the world's population, and the Southern Ocean overturning circulation has historically received much less attention than the AMOC.
[src:ocean-modeling/thermohaline-circulation] There has been a suggestion that its collapse may occur between 1.7 °C (3.1 °F) and 3 °C (5.4 °F), but this estimate is much less certain than for many other tipping points.
